  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The U.N.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Security Council today overwhelmingly approved sweeping trade and military sanctions against Iraq, including a ban on oil purchases, to punish Baghdad for invading Kuwait.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The vote was 13-0, with two abstentions by Cuba and Yemen on the 15-member council, which adopted the sanctions resolution proposed by the United States.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   It was the third time in its 45-year existence that the world body had voted sanctions against a member state.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The sanctions are legally binding for all member nations, although past council resolutions have often been ignored or flouted.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   The council includes the five permanent members with veto power - the United States, Britain, China, France and the Soviet Union.
  </a>
